A different display of delays

Consider the flights dataset from the nycflights13 dataset. In this exercise, you have to experiment with the tile geometric object (which you can access using the function geom_tile, for instance), which covers the plot with many small rectangles, one for each combination of values of x and y. We can leverage this to build a different visualization of the average delay for each day, with the fill color of each tile encoding the average delay. Complete the following code block.

# Map `day` to the `x` aesthetic, `month` to the `y` aesthetic and 
# the average of `dep_delay` to the `fill` aesthetic
flights %>%
group_by(month, day) %>%
summarise(dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
ggplot(aes(
        x= day , # Complete the aesthetic mapping
        y= month  , 
        fill= dep_delay
)) +
    geom_tile()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Now you should do the same without using the preprocessing pipeline. In particular, you should use a stat_summary_2d layer. Read the help page of stat_summary_2d to learn how to use the x, y and z aesthetic mappings to replicate the plot above. Note that since in this dataste months and days are encoded as numbers, but stat_summary_2d works best with discrete values, you will have to use factor(month) and factor(day) in your aesthetic mapping in place of month and day.

# Your solution here
flights %>%
group_by(month, day) %>%
summarise(dep_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
ggplot(aes(
            x= factor(day) , 
            y= factor(month)  , 
            z= dep_delay,)) +
    geom_tile() + stat_summary_2d() 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Experimental results analysis

In this exercise, you will play the role of a computer scientist comparing the running time of two different algorithms to multiply dense matrices, namely naive and strassen, for different sizes of their inputs. However, you don’t know if naive is faster than strassen. Therefore, you ran the following experiment: you consider values of the input size n in the set 2,4,8,16,32,64,128,256,512,1024,2048. For each value of n each algorithm is run 10 times, recording the running time in nanoseconds. Therefore, you collect 10 different time measurements for input size 10 for naive, and 10 different time measurements for input size 10 for strassen.

The csv file experiment.csv contains the results of this experiment. You can load the data in this file using read_csv("experiment.csv"), there are no missing values. Your task in this exercise is to explore and visualize this experimental data, with the aim of answering the following question:

Is strassen faster than naive?

After looking at the data with the View function, here are a few things you can try out:

  • Plot using the line geom with the time on the y axis and n on the x axis. You can use color to distinguish between the two algorithms. Beware that for each value of n there are several measurements, so you might want to compute some summary statistic.
experiment%>%
ggplot(aes(x = n, y = time, color = algorithm)) +
geom_line()

- Try to add points on top of the lines, as a new layer.

experiment%>%
ggplot(aes(x = n, y = time, color = algorithm)) +
geom_line() + geom_point()

  • Use log scales on the x and y axis, possibly on both. For the x axis try to use a logarthmic scale in base 2, using scale_x_continuous(trans="log2")
experiment%>%
ggplot(aes(x = n, y = time, color = algorithm)) +
geom_line(stat = "summary") + geom_point(stat = "summary")+
scale_x_continuous(trans = "log2")

- Compute, for each value of n, the ratio between the average time of naive and the average time of strassen. You might need to use pivot_wider on the data before building the plot. Then, plot these ratios on the y axis and the value of n on the x axis. You can also add a horizontal line at ratio 1 using the layer geom_hline(yintercept=1) What is this plot displaying?

For each point in the list above create a new code block and write the code to create the plot following the hint.

experiment%>%
 group_by(algorithm, n)%>%
 summarise(time = mean(time))%>%
 pivot_wider(names_from = algorithm, values_from = time)%>%
 mutate(ratio = naive /strassen)%>%
 mutate(c = if_else(ratio <1, "blue", "red"))%>%
  
ggplot(experiment,mapping = aes(x = n, y = ratio, color = c)) +
 geom_line(stat = "summary") +
 geom_point(stat = "summary") +
 geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = "dotted") +
 scale_color_identity() + 
 scale_x_continuous(trans = "log2") +
 scale_y_continuous(trans ="log10")
